"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 6–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-6-10.py

Covers: ANE/historical background, geography, archaeology, cultural context
NOT: Hebrew grammar (mkt-original) or Christological typology (mkt-christ)

Key contextual clusters:
- Ch 6: high places (bamot) and their archaeology; Assyrian/Babylonian campaign devastation;
  the mountains of Israel as cult landscape
- Ch 7: Day of YHWH traditions; economic collapse in siege context; ANE destruction rhetoric
- Ch 8: four idolatrous practices in the Jerusalem temple — image of jealousy (possibly Asherah
  or the statue of Manasseh), secret chamber incense-worship (elders), Tammuz weeping
  (Mesopotamian fertility cult), sun-worship to the east (solar cult); all archaeologically attested
- Ch 9: the six executioners + scribe; tau-marking of the faithful; ANE apotropaic marking;
  divine abandonment as judgment pattern
- Ch 10: the throne-chariot revisited; the coal-taking from the altar; comparison with ch 1
  details; the glory beginning its departure eastward
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
"6": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 6 opens the first oracle specifically against &quot;the mountains of Israel&quot; — the geographic landscape of the nation framed as a cultic entity. The mountains had been the primary sites of Israel&apos;s illicit worship since the settlement period: the high places (<em>bamot</em>) were typically hilltop installations that preceded and persisted alongside the Jerusalem temple. Archaeological surveys have identified dozens of such sites across Canaan, ranging from simple stone circles to elaborate platforms with standing stones and cultic vessels.</p>",
"2": "<p>The command to set the face against the mountains invokes the oracular convention of addressing inanimate geography as a guilty party. This rhetorical form — borrowed from ancient Near Eastern covenant-lawsuit traditions — treats the landscape as the witness and participant in Israel&apos;s covenant violation. The mountains and hills, valleys and ravines that receive YHWH&apos;s sword are the actual geographical features of the land on which the idolatrous worship occurred.</p>",
"3": "<p>The <em>bamot</em> (high places) were elevated installations throughout Israel&apos;s history. Archaeological excavations at Megiddo, Gezer, Hazor, Arad, and Beersheba have uncovered cultic platforms, standing stones (<em>massevot</em>), incense altars, and votive figurines associated with these sites. The Israelite high places combined Canaanite architectural conventions with adapted YHWH-worship, and their destruction was the defining criterion of royal evaluation in Kings: &quot;the high places were not removed.&quot; Ezekiel&apos;s oracle envisions their final abolition by enemy destruction.</p>",
"4": "<p>The altars (<em>mizbeḥot</em>) and incense altars (<em>ḥammanim</em>) — the <em>ḥammanim</em> (singular <em>ḥamman</em>) are small limestone incense stands found archaeologically throughout the Iron Age Levant. The term may derive from <em>ḥamman</em> (sun, heat) suggesting solar-cult association; over 200 examples have been identified in Palestinian excavation contexts. Their destruction alongside the main altars indicates that both the large sacrificial installations and the portable incense-worship equipment are included in the judgment.</p>",
"5": "<p>The corpses strewn before the idols — YHWH literally fulfilling what these worshipers feared their gods would exact: death at the sacred precincts. ANE ritual texts describe the gods as requiring the slaughter of their enemies; here YHWH brings the worshipers&apos; own bodies before the idols they served, inverting the logic of the cult. The bones scattered around the altars desecrate the sacred space — a deliberate profanation mirroring the profanation of YHWH&apos;s sanctuary.</p>",
"6": "<p>The comprehensive destruction of every cultic installation — wherever Israel dwells, &quot;the cities will be laid waste and the high places made desolate.&quot; The agricultural calendar of the ancient economy depended on the fertility cult practiced at these high places — rain for crops, fecundity for flocks. The destruction of the cult sites thus represents not only religious but also economic catastrophe in the popular understanding. Ezekiel overturns this assumption: YHWH, not Baal, controls the rain and harvest.</p>",
"7": "<p>The recognition formula — &quot;they will know that I am YHWH&quot; — appears here for the first time in the judgment against the mountains. This formula, occurring ~72 times in Ezekiel, is the stated purpose of every judgment: YHWH&apos;s identity is established through historical events when his word is vindicated by fulfillment. For the nations who witness Israel&apos;s fall, and for the survivors, the Babylonian conquest is YHWH&apos;s identity-disclosure, not a defeat of YHWH by Marduk.</p>",
"8": "<p>The remnant promise — &quot;some of you will escape the sword among the nations&quot; — introduces the first hint of survival within the judgment oracle. The diaspora survivors scattered among the nations (a reality Ezekiel&apos;s audience already experienced from their side as exiles in Babylon) are YHWH&apos;s instrument for preserving testimony to what occurred.</p>",
"9": "<p>The memory and loathing of the heart among the scattered survivors — <strong>&quot;those who escape will remember me among the nations where they have been carried captive.&quot;</strong> The psychology of exile described here is well attested in the literature of the Babylonian deportation period: Ps 137 (&quot;by the rivers of Babylon&quot;) and the lament psalms reflect the spiritual crisis of worship without temple and land. Ezekiel&apos;s vision of future repentance (the heart that has played the whore remembering and loathing itself) is the inner dimension of the outer restoration.</p>",
"10": "<p>The declaration that YHWH did not speak in vain (<em>lo hinnam dibbartim</em>) reinforces the prophetic claim against the community&apos;s dismissal of the prophetic word (cf. 12:22-28). The Babylonian exile confirmed to those who survived that the pre-exilic prophets had been telling the truth — a recognition that shaped the formation of the prophetic canon.</p>",
"11": "<p>The command to clap, stamp, and cry &quot;Alas!&quot; (<em>ʾah</em>) — Ezekiel himself performing the mourning gestures — is one of several enacted laments in the book. The prophetic body enacts what the community will experience. ANE mourning rituals involved striking the thigh, clapping, beating the chest; these gestures appear in funerary iconography across Mesopotamia and Egypt. Ezekiel&apos;s performance of mourning before the fact is part of his role as the one whose body embodies the communal fate.</p>",
"12": "<p>The tripartite judgment formula — those far off by plague, those near by sword, those remaining besieged by famine — covers all geographic positions relative to Jerusalem. The three-part death formula (plague/sword/famine) is a standard totality-expression in Ezekiel and Jeremiah. Together they describe a siege situation comprehensively: those outside the city fall to the Babylonian army, those inside starve or succumb to epidemic.</p>",
"13": "<p>The specific cultic sites where the corpses will lie — &quot;wherever they offered pleasing odor to all their idols, on every high hill, on all the mountaintops, under every green tree, under every leafy oak&quot; — is a catalog of the landscape of Canaanite and syncretistic Israelite worship. The &quot;green tree&quot; and &quot;leafy oak&quot; motifs appear throughout the prophetic literature (Isa 57:5; Jer 2:20; 3:6, 13; 17:2; Hos 4:13) as stereotyped references to outdoor fertility-cult worship sites. The specific mention of the pleasing odor (<em>reyaḥ nihoaḥ</em>) being offered to idols parodies the same phrase used for acceptable YHWH-worship (Lev 1:9, 13, 17).</p>",
"14": "<p>The destruction extending &quot;from the wilderness to Riblah&quot; — or possibly &quot;Diblah&quot; in some manuscript traditions — defines the full territorial scope. Riblah in Syria (on the Orontes) was Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s military headquarters during the 586 BCE siege campaign, the site where Zedekiah was blinded and his sons killed (2 Kgs 25:6-7). The phrase &quot;more desolate than the wilderness&quot; reflects the complete devastation of all settled agricultural territory — not merely the urban centers but the entire inhabited landscape.</p>"
},
"7": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 7 announces &quot;the end&quot; (<em>haqqets</em>) — a term loaded with prophetic eschatological weight. The &quot;end&quot; language is not apocalyptic in the later Jewish sense but refers to the finality of a historical catastrophe: the end of the Davidic kingdom, the end of the temple-era, the end of the land&apos;s covenant security. The threefold repetition of the end-announcement (vv2, 3, 6) creates the relentless rhetorical momentum of a doom oracle.</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;An end — the end has come upon the four corners of the land&quot; — the four-corners idiom (also Isa 11:12; Job 37:3) indicates the totality of the geographical territory. In ANE cosmography, the &quot;four corners of the earth&quot; was the standard expression for the entire inhabited world. Applied to Israel&apos;s land, it declares that no part of the territory will escape the coming judgment.</p>",
"3": "<p>&quot;Now the end is upon you&quot; — the second-person direct address shifts from the mountains (ch 6) to the land/people as a unified addressee. The judgment criteria named here — your ways (<em>derakhayikh</em>) and your abominations (<em>toʿavotayikh</em>) — are the twin categories of covenant violation throughout Ezekiel: behavioral patterns and cultic corruption.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;My eye will not spare you, nor will I have pity&quot; — the divine non-compassion formula appears repeatedly in Ezekiel&apos;s judgment oracles (5:11; 7:4, 9; 8:18; 9:5, 10). This is not cruelty but judicial finality: the covenant curses (Lev 26; Deut 28) warned that persistent violation would eventually exhaust the period of divine patience. The expression mirrors identical language in Deuteronomy 13:8 (the command not to spare a family member who leads to idolatry) — YHWH applies to himself the same judicial standard he required of Israel.</p>",
"5": "<p>&quot;Disaster after disaster&quot; — the unusual Hebrew phrase (<em>raʿah ʾaḥat raʿah</em>, a unique evil coming) marks the unprecedented quality of the event. Babylon&apos;s 586 BCE destruction of Jerusalem was indeed historically unparalleled in Israel&apos;s experience: no previous foreign conquest had combined the destruction of the temple, the removal of the Davidic king, and the mass deportation of the population.</p>",
"6": "<p>The end-vocabulary climaxes with a wordplay: <em>haqqets</em> (the end) and <em>heqits</em> (has awakened/roused itself). The divine awakening against Israel is the awakening of the covenant lawsuit. ANE treaties regularly envisioned the divine treaty-witnesses as &quot;sleeping&quot; gods who must be aroused to witness violations; Ezekiel subverts this by portraying YHWH as the one who rouses the judgment himself.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;The morning has come for you, O inhabitant of the land&quot; — the <em>tsefira</em> (crown/morning) here is ironic: it should denote the glory of the day but instead introduces judgment. The &quot;day of YHWH&quot; tradition in the pre-exilic prophets (Amos 5:18-20; Isa 2; Joel 1-2; Zeph 1) consistently inverted popular expectations: Israel anticipated the Day of YHWH as vindication over enemies, but the prophets declared it as judgment against Israel itself. Chapter 7 is Ezekiel&apos;s contribution to this tradition.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;I will pour out my wrath upon you, complete my anger against you&quot; — the poured-out-wrath idiom appears 14 times in Ezekiel (7:8; 9:8; 14:19; 20:8, 13, 21, 33-34; 22:22, 31; 36:18) and is related to the libation-pouring of the cult inverted as judgment. Pouring was the consecrating act of worship (wine, oil, blood); YHWH&apos;s pouring of wrath parodies the pour-offering with its own covenant vocabulary.</p>",
"9": "<p>The third announcement of total judgment and the recognition formula (they will know YHWH is the one who smites them) complete the opening triad. The recognition of YHWH as the agent behind the Babylonian invasion is the theological counter-claim to Babylonian victory theology, which attributed the conquest to Marduk&apos;s superiority. Ezekiel&apos;s oracle insists that Nebuchadnezzar is YHWH&apos;s instrument, not Marduk&apos;s triumph.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;The rod has blossomed, pride has budded&quot; — the rod (<em>matteh</em>) may refer to Babylon (YHWH&apos;s instrument of judgment) or to Israel&apos;s own pride. The blossoming-rod imagery may be an ironic inversion of Aaron&apos;s rod that budded (Num 17:8) as a sign of divinely chosen leadership: here the budding rod signals judgment rather than divine favor.</p>",
"11": "<p>&quot;Violence has grown up into a rod of wickedness&quot; — the economic and social violence (<em>ḥamas</em>) of pre-exilic Judah is consistently cited by the prophets as a reason for the exile (Mic 3:10; Isa 1:21-23; Jer 7:9). Archaeological evidence from the pre-exilic period confirms the social stratification and exploitation that the prophets condemned: large grain storage facilities at royal sites alongside impoverishment of rural populations documented in ostraca from Samaria and Arad.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;The time has come, the day draws near — let not the buyer rejoice, nor the seller mourn&quot; — this economic disruption describes the collapse of the normal commercial cycle under siege conditions. In peacetime, real estate transactions in ancient Israel were carefully regulated (Lev 25; Jer 32); the coming judgment will make all such economic arrangements irrelevant. The land-release ordinances of the Jubilee will be superseded by the comprehensive land-forfeiture of exile.</p>",
"13": "<p>The seller will not return to the sold property even if still living — the normal jubilee-restoration mechanism is suspended by the totality of the judgment. The vision (<em>ḥazon</em>) concerning the whole multitude will not be reversed: no individual exemptions, no partial redemptions. The Babylonian administration of conquered territories routinely redistributed land to deportees and local populations — the pre-exilic property arrangements were permanently disrupted by conquest.</p>",
"14": "<p>&quot;They have blown the trumpet and made all ready, but no one goes to battle&quot; — the military trumpet call was the standard mobilization signal in ancient Near Eastern armies (also Jer 4:5, 19; Joel 2:1; Amos 3:6). The failure of response to the trumpet blast — no one goes to the battle despite the mobilization signal — represents the complete military demoralization of the Judean forces before Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s army.</p>",
"15": "<p>Sword outside, plague and famine inside — the classic siege-situation compressed into a single verse. Siege warfare in the ancient world typically killed more through disease and starvation than through direct military assault. The account of Jerusalem&apos;s fall in 2 Kings 25 and Lamentations confirms this pattern: famine was the dominant cause of civilian suffering during the 18-month siege of 588-586 BCE.</p>",
"16": "<p>The survivors on the mountains mourning like doves — the dove-mourning imagery appears in Isa 38:14 and 59:11 for mournful sighing. The mountains to which survivors flee are the same mountains addressed in ch 6: the sites of the cult that provoked the judgment become the places of desperate refuge when the judgment comes.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;All hands will be feeble, and all knees will be weak as water&quot; — the physical manifestation of panic in ANE literature is consistently expressed through the same physiological vocabulary: weakened hands, trembling knees, running water (urine from fear). Nahum 2:10 uses the same triad for Nineveh&apos;s fall. The somatic description of communal terror reflects actual physiological responses to extreme fear documented across cultures.</p>",
"18": "<p>Sackcloth and horror covering them — the mourning-garment (<em>saq</em>) was worn for both personal bereavement and communal disaster (2 Sam 3:31; Jonah 3:5-8; Jer 6:26). The shaved heads (<em>qorḥah</em>) and shame on all faces (<em>bushet ʿal-kol-phanim</em>) complete the mourning posture. Shaving the head was the standard sign of extreme grief across the ancient Near East, documented in Egyptian and Mesopotamian funerary texts as well as throughout the OT.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;They throw their silver into the streets and their gold is treated as unclean (<em>niddah</em>)&quot; — the economic collapse of a besieged city in its final stages: the monetary metals that accumulated Israel&apos;s prosperity become useless when food cannot be purchased. The term <em>niddah</em> (menstrual uncleanness, the strongest impurity category in Levitical law) applied to gold indicates the total inversion of values: the most precious becomes the most polluted. The hoarded wealth cannot buy food in a city cut off by siege.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;Their beautiful ornament they used for pride, and they made their abominable images from it&quot; — the temple treasures and personal ornaments of pre-exilic Jerusalem were both symbols of YHWH&apos;s blessing and (in the prophetic critique) raw material for the idol-manufacture that corrupted the worship. Archaeological finds from the pre-exilic period include numerous bronze figurines and worked metal devotional objects that represent the popular religion the prophets condemned.</p>",
"21": "<p>The handing of the wealth to foreigners as plunder — the Babylonian looting of Jerusalem&apos;s treasuries and temple is documented in 2 Kings 25:13-17 and in the Babylonian Chronicle. The temple vessels, the bronze pillars, and the royal treasury all went to Babylon; the book of Daniel (Dan 1:2) notes specifically that Nebuchadnezzar brought &quot;vessels of the house of God&quot; to the temple of his god in Babylon.</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;I will turn my face from them&quot; — the divine face-turning is the opposite of the priestly blessing (&quot;YHWH make his face shine upon you,&quot; Num 6:25-26). The temple as YHWH&apos;s &quot;treasured place&quot; (<em>tsefoni</em>) which will be profaned by robbers — the reference is to the temple treasury, the <em>beit hamiqddash</em> that housed the donated treasures and was the ultimate target of conquering armies.</p>",
"23": "<p>&quot;Make the chain&quot; — the fettering of captives for deportation. Assyrian and Babylonian reliefs consistently depict captured peoples being led away with ropes or chains around their necks, a visual convention for the humiliation of conquest. The land is &quot;full of bloody crimes&quot; (<em>mishpat damim</em>) and the city full of violence (<em>ḥamas</em>) — the same double condemnation (judicial corruption + social violence) that characterizes the pre-exilic prophetic indictment.</p>",
"24": "<p>&quot;I will bring the worst of the nations&quot; — Babylon is identified elsewhere in Ezekiel as the instrument of judgment (21:19-27; 29:18-20). The &quot;worst of the nations&quot; (<em>raʿ haggoyim</em>) reflects the moral condemnation of Babylon even as it is YHWH&apos;s instrument — the Babylonian empire itself was not exempt from divine judgment (Jer 25:12; 50-51). Their taking possession of the houses and making the pride of the strong to cease is the conquest-theology of the ancient world articulated in prophetic terms.</p>",
"25": "<p>&quot;When anguish comes, they will seek peace and find none&quot; — the failure to find <em>shalom</em> after the judgment falls is the ironic fulfillment of the false prophets&apos; promise of <em>shalom</em> (13:10, 16). Those who sought peace through alliance politics (Egypt) and through false prophets will find that authentic peace only comes through YHWH&apos;s restoration, not through political maneuvering in the crisis.</p>",
"26": "<p>&quot;Disaster after disaster, rumor after rumor&quot; — the cascading-catastrophe description reflects the experience of rapid conquest. The speed of Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s campaigns is documented in the Babylonian Chronicle: the Babylonian army could cover enormous distances rapidly, leaving besieged cities with little time to organize resistance. The failure of all three oracular sources (vision from the prophet, law from the priest, counsel from the elders) in the crisis reflects the collapse of the institutional infrastructure of Judean society.</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;The king mourns, the prince is clothed in despair, the hands of the people of the land are paralyzed with terror&quot; — the social hierarchy dismantled from top to bottom. Zedekiah&apos;s actual capture and humiliation (2 Kgs 25:4-7) fulfilled this precisely: the king fled, was caught, saw his sons killed before his eyes, was blinded, and was led in chains to Babylon. The prince (the crown prince or the nobility), the common people — all experience the same desolation that distinguishes no rank.</p>"
},
"8": {
"1": "<p>The vision of ch 8 occurs in the sixth year, sixth month, fifth day — September/October 592 BCE — fourteen months after the initial commission vision (1:2). The elders of Judah sitting before Ezekiel in his exile house at Tel-abib represent the community&apos;s use of the prophet as an oracle-consultant — the normal function of a prophetic figure in the ANE world. The Spirit&apos;s transport of Ezekiel to Jerusalem (v3) is the vision-journey genre common in ancient apocalyptic literature, in which the seer is transported to see heavenly or distant realities.</p>",
"2": "<p>The figure of fire from the loins downward and brightness upward — a theophanic appearance identical to the glory-figure of 1:27. The description in v2 anchors the vision firmly in the throne-chariot framework of ch 1: the guide is the glory-figure of YHWH himself, or a representation of it, conducting the vision-tour. The fiery lower half / bright upper half contrast may reflect ancient iconography of divinity: Mesopotamian and Canaanite divine figures are often depicted with flames at their base and light emanating from their heads.</p>",
"3": "<p>The stretched-out hand and the transport to Jerusalem by the Spirit — the lock of hair (<em>tsitsit roʾshi</em>) by which Ezekiel is grabbed is a distinctive detail suggesting the physicality and urgency of the prophetic transport. The Spirit-transport formula here (<em>wayyiqaḥ ʾoti betsissit roʾshi wayyissaʾ ʾoti ruaḥ</em>) combines the hand-grasp with the Spirit-lift, distinguishing this entry into the vision from the prior episodes where only the Spirit lifts. The north gate of the inner court was the primary entrance for worshipers — the location of the &quot;image of jealousy&quot; means it was encountered by every worshiper entering the sanctuary precinct.</p>",
"4": "<p>The glory of YHWH (<em>kavod</em>) appearing in the inner court — the divine presence that Ezekiel last saw at Tel-abib (chs 1-3) is now visible within the Jerusalem temple itself. The irony is devastating: YHWH is present in his own temple to witness the abominations being committed in it. The vision establishes that YHWH sees and knows what occurs in the temple, even the secret practices in hidden chambers (v12).</p>",
"5": "<p>The image of jealousy (<em>semel haqqinʾah</em>) at the north gateway entrance — the noun <em>semel</em> (image/likeness) appears in Deut 4:16 for idols in general; combined with <em>qinʾah</em> (jealousy) it suggests the idol that provokes YHWH&apos;s jealousy. The leading candidates based on historical context are: (1) the Asherah pole installed by Manasseh (2 Kgs 21:7), (2) a goddess-statue (possibly Asherah/Astarte) set up in the temple gate area, or (3) a cult image of Baal. The north gate location is significant because the north is associated with divine assembly in Canaanite mythology (Baal&apos;s mountain Zaphon = north).</p>",
"6": "<p>The question &quot;Do you see what they are doing — great abominations that drive me far from my sanctuary?&quot; — the divine analysis is that the abominations actively drive YHWH away. This is the theological foundation for the glory-departure vision of chs 10-11: the idolatry does not merely coexist with YHWH&apos;s presence but is causally responsible for removing it. The spatial metaphor of &quot;driving far&quot; (<em>lemarḥaqah meʿal miqdashi</em>) is the inverse of the nearness-of-YHWH language of Deuteronomy.</p>",
"7": "<p>The hole in the wall at the temple entrance — Ezekiel is told to dig through the wall to find the entrance to a hidden chamber. This detail grounds the vision in the architecture of the Jerusalem temple precinct. Archaeological excavations around the Temple Mount and in pre-exilic Jerusalem (the Ophel area) have revealed complex systems of storage rooms, side chambers, and administrative spaces adjoining the temple — the kind of spaces where secret priestly activity could occur out of public sight.</p>",
"8": "<p>The digging through the wall — the same verb (<em>ḥatar</em>) used for the prince digging through the wall in the exile sign-act of 12:5, 7, 12 — creates an intertextual link: the secret access to the temple&apos;s idolatry mirrors the forced exit from Jerusalem in siege. Both involve digging through walls as illicit entries/exits.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Go in and see the wicked abominations that they are doing here&quot; — the progressive revelation structure of the vision (four increasingly shocking abominations shown in sequence) is a literary technique that builds theological case. The repetition of &quot;you will see yet greater abominations&quot; (vv6, 13, 15) creates the escalating horror of the prophetic disclosure.</p>",
"10": "<p>The chambers filled with carvings of creeping things, abominable animals, and all the idols of the house of Israel — the wall-to-wall animal and idol imagery in the secret priestly chambers has been connected to several ANE traditions: (1) Egyptian animal iconography (crocodiles, ibises, scarabs) that appeared in the Hellenized Levant; (2) Mesopotamian protective animal imagery used in the apotropaic ritual traditions that came into Judah; (3) the animal cult imagery associated with the Asherah cult. The 70 elders performing this secret incense worship suggest a priestly college maintaining an alternative sacrificial tradition.</p>",
"11": "<p>The seventy elders of the house of Israel burning incense — the number 70 is the complete council of elders (Exod 24:1, 9; Num 11:16, 24-25). Jaazaniah son of Shaphan is specifically named: the Shaphan family were prominent royal officials under Josiah (2 Kgs 22:3ff.) who supported the reform; a son of Shaphan practicing secret idolatry represents the complete failure of even the reform movement&apos;s legacy. The dark-room incense burning (<em>be-ḥasheikh ish becheder maskhito</em>, &quot;each man in his room of images&quot;) echoes the widespread practice of household shrines and private devotional objects documented archaeologically in pre-exilic household archaeology.</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;YHWH does not see us; YHWH has forsaken the land&quot; — the theology behind the secret worship: the elders concluded that YHWH had abandoned the land (possibly after the first deportation of 597 BCE), making worship of other gods pragmatically necessary. This crisis-pluralism — seeking insurance from multiple divine patrons when one&apos;s primary deity seems to have failed — is well documented in the ancient world. The Lachish Letters (ostraca from the final years of Jerusalem) show a community at the breaking point of the old covenant certainties.</p>",
"13": "<p>The third abomination: women weeping for Tammuz (<em>Tammuz</em>) at the north gate. Tammuz (Sumerian Dumuzid) was the Mesopotamian shepherd-deity whose annual death (into the underworld) was mourned in midsummer ritual. The Akkadian name <em>Dumuzi</em>/Tammuz appears in Babylonian religious texts from the third millennium onward; the fourth month of the Babylonian calendar was named after him, and his cult involved ritual lamentation by women, sacred marriage rites, and fertility themes. The presence of this cult at the Jerusalem temple gate reflects the penetration of Babylonian religious practices into Judean life during the Assyrian and Babylonian periods.</p>",
"14": "<p>The location at the north gate entrance — the same gate where the image of jealousy stood (v5) — concentrates the abominations at the primary public entrance point. The north gate was both the main access to the inner court and, in Canaanite cosmology, the direction associated with divine assembly (Zaphon). The ritual lamentation for Tammuz at this gate combines Mesopotamian fertility religion with the sacred geography of the Jerusalem temple precinct.</p>",
"15": "<p>The fourth and &quot;greatest&quot; abomination: twenty-five men at the inner court&apos;s east entrance, between the portico and the altar, with their backs to YHWH&apos;s temple, worshiping the sun toward the east. Solar worship in the pre-exilic Jerusalem cult is documented by the Horses of the Sun kept near the temple entrance (2 Kgs 23:11, removed by Josiah). The positioning — backs to the temple, faces east — represents a deliberate liturgical inversion: the normal posture of temple worship faced west toward the Most Holy Place; these worshipers orient themselves toward the rising sun instead.</p>",
"16": "<p>The precise location — between the <em>ʾulam</em> (portico) and the <em>mizbeaḥ</em> (altar) — is the priests&apos; space, the zone accessible only to the priesthood. The twenty-five may correspond to the priestly courses or to a high-priestly council. Their sun-worship at the sacred heart of the priestly precinct represents the highest level of cultic corruption: the very men responsible for maintaining YHWH&apos;s worship are conducting a rival solar liturgy in the most sacred priestly space.</p>",
"17": "<p>&quot;Is it too light a thing for the house of Judah to commit the abominations they commit here, that they should fill the land with violence?&quot; — YHWH&apos;s rhetorical question connects the cultic abominations of the temple with the social violence (<em>ḥamas</em>) condemned throughout the book. The &quot;branch to the nose&quot; (<em>meshalḥim ʾet-hazzemorah ʾel-ʾappam</em>) is obscure — it may refer to an offensive gesture in a ritual context, a Zoroastrian influence (holding a barsom bundle to the nose in sun worship), or a defiant gesture toward YHWH.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;Therefore I will act in wrath; my eye will not spare, nor will I have pity&quot; — the non-compassion formula of v4 is repeated with the specific motivation of the cultic abominations now cataloged. The conclusion — &quot;though they cry in my ears with a loud voice, I will not hear them&quot; — is the reverse of the Shema: Israel&apos;s crying out will receive no divine response, because they cried out to their foreign gods rather than to YHWH. The refusal to hear corresponds to Israel&apos;s refusal to hear YHWH&apos;s word through the prophets.</p>"
},
"9": {
"1": "<p>The vision of the executioners follows immediately from the abomination-tour of ch 8. The six men with &quot;weapons of destruction&quot; (<em>keli mashḥit</em>) are angelic agents — not human soldiers. The figure of the man with the writing case (<em>qeset hasofer</em>) is distinct from the six executioners and has a protective function. The sequence — first mark the innocent, then execute the guilty — reflects the principle of judicial discrimination that runs throughout Ezekiel&apos;s theology of individual accountability.</p>",
"2": "<p>The six men come from the north by way of the upper gate — the north gate, the location of the abominations of ch 8. The north is both the direction from which Babylon comes (1:4) and the direction of the divine assembly mount (Zaphon). The weapons in their hands — likely clubs or maces (<em>keli mashḥit</em>) — are the standard close-combat weapons of ancient Near Eastern military forces, depicted on Assyrian and Babylonian reliefs. The man in linen with the writing case is distinctly priestly in his attire (linen was the priestly fabric) and scribal in his function.</p>",
"3": "<p>The glory of YHWH moving from the cherub to the threshold of the temple — the first movement of the divine glory-departure sequence that will culminate in 10:18-19 and 11:22-23. The departure is gradual and reluctant, not sudden: YHWH moves step by step away from the sanctuary. This theological narrative of graduated withdrawal reflects the covenant-curse dynamic of Leviticus 26: increasingly severe consequences for increasing faithlessness, with YHWH always leaving space for repentance.</p>",
"4": "<p>The tau mark (<em>tav</em>) placed on the foreheads of those who mourn the abominations — in the paleo-Hebrew script of the pre-exilic period, the letter <em>tav</em> (ת) was written as an X or + cross-shape. The protective marking of the faithful before judgment is a widespread motif in ANE tradition: the Passover blood on doorposts (Exod 12:22-23), the scarlet thread in Rahab&apos;s window (Josh 2:18), and Cain&apos;s mark (Gen 4:15) are the OT parallels. The tau on the forehead of the faithful reverses the forehead-mark of idolatry that brands those condemned in v6.</p>",
"5": "<p>The command to the executioners — &quot;follow him through the city and strike&quot; — establishes the sequence: first the scribe marks the faithful, then the executioners follow and kill all who lack the mark. This sequential structure is the narrative basis for the distinction between the faithful remnant and the condemned majority. The command in v5 begins the execution phase immediately after the protective marking, indicating that both marking and execution happen simultaneously in the city.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Kill old men, young men, young women, little children, and women — but do not touch anyone who has the mark&quot; — the non-discrimination of age or sex in the judgment (all unmarked die) combined with the absolute protection of the marked establishes the criterion of individual faithfulness as the only determinant of survival. The starting point — the elders (the twenty-five of 8:16) before the temple — inverts the standard royal-ideology of honor toward elders. Here the elders at the sacred space are the first to die, not the last protected.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;Defile the temple and fill the courts with the slain&quot; — the command to kill in the temple precincts is the final profanation of the already-profaned sanctuary. Killing in the temple court was the most extreme impurity — corpse-defilement in the holy space compounded with blood-shedding. The command to go out and execute through the city reverses the temple&apos;s function as a sanctuary/asylum: normally the temple precincts were a zone of protection; here they become the site of judgment.</p>",
"8": "<p>Ezekiel&apos;s intercession — &quot;Will you destroy all the remnant of Israel?&quot; — is one of the rare moments in Ezekiel when the prophet exercises the traditional intercessory function. The fact that YHWH explicitly denies the intercession (in contrast to the successful intercessions of Moses) is a measure of how far the judgment has proceeded. The iniquity of the house of Israel and Judah is &quot;very very great&quot; — the double intensifier (<em>gadol badmeʾod meʾod</em>) expresses the superlative degree of accumulated covenant violation.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;The land is full of blood, the city full of injustice&quot; — the double condemnation of blood-guilt (judicial murder, violence) and social injustice (<em>matteh mishpat</em>, perversion of justice) maps to the twin prophetic categories of cultic and social failure. YHWH&apos;s non-seeing in the elders&apos; theology (8:12) is here turned back against them: they claimed YHWH had forsaken the land and did not see; now YHWH declares that he sees very well (<em>reʾeh raʾiti</em>, &quot;I have indeed seen&quot;), and what he sees warrants the judgment.</p>",
"10": "<p>The repetition of the non-pity/non-sparing formula from 8:18 in the context of the execution vision confirms the theological continuity: the divine refusal of compassion is not arbitrary but follows directly from the accumulated evidence of the cultic abominations tour. The &quot;deed&quot; returned on their own heads (<em>darkam berosham natati</em>) is the lex-talionis principle applied to corporate Israel.</p>",
"11": "<p>The man in linen reporting back — &quot;I have done as you commanded me&quot; — is the first clear instance in the vision of a completed divine command. The reporting formula (<em>vayyashev davar leʾmor ʿasiti kaʾasher tsivvitani</em>) uses the same vocabulary as obedient human execution of divine commands (cf. Ezekiel&apos;s own obedience reports: 12:7; 24:18; 37:7, 10). The angelic obedience provides the literary closure of the execution-vision begun in v2.</p>"
},
"10": {
"1": "<p>The vision of the throne-chariot revisited — the expanse above the heads of the cherubim (1:22-26 vocabulary) reappears here. The comparison to sapphire (<em>keʾeven sappir</em>) is the same descriptor used in 1:26. Chapter 10 is a reprise of the chapter 1 vision but now contextualized within the Jerusalem temple rather than the Babylonian plain: the throne-chariot is inside the temple courts, preparing to depart. The throne-chariot&apos;s presence in the temple reflects the OT tradition of the divine warrior&apos;s chariot-throne (Ps 68:17-18) entering the sanctuary.</p>",
"2": "<p>The man in linen commanded to take coals from between the cherubim and scatter them over the city — the coal-taking is the act of judgment that corresponds to the purification in Isa 6:6 (the coal from the altar purifies the prophet&apos;s lips) but here the coals scattered over Jerusalem indicate burning judgment rather than cleansing. The Babylonian burning of Jerusalem (2 Kgs 25:9) is the historical event this action foreshadows: the city was literally burned when it fell in 586 BCE.</p>",
"3": "<p>The position of the cherubim — on the south side of the temple when the man entered — is the side of the altar of burnt offerings (the outer altar stood in the south portion of the inner court). The cloud filling the inner court when the glory moved from the cherub to the temple threshold (v4) is the standard theophanic cloud of divine presence (Exod 40:34-35; 1 Kgs 8:10-11). The filling of the house with the cloud and the court with the brightness of divine glory echoes the Solomonic dedication-narrative, but here it is the prelude to departure rather than arrival.</p>",
"4": "<p>The glory of YHWH rising from the cherub to the threshold — the first step of the departure sequence. The cloud and brightness filling the temple is a transitional state: the glory is not yet departed but is in motion, lifting off from the cherub-throne to the threshold. The threshold is the liminal space between the temple&apos;s interior holiness and the court — a theologically significant intermediate position.</p>",
"5": "<p>The sound of the wings of the cherubim heard in the outer court like the voice of God Almighty (<em>El Shaddai</em>) — the divine name <em>El Shaddai</em> appears only here in Ezekiel. The name is associated with the patriarchal period and with divine power (Gen 17:1; 28:3; 35:11; Exod 6:3). Its use here marks the sound of the departing glory as the unmistakable voice of the divine power-name — the cherubim&apos;s wings create a sound equivalent to the divine speech.</p>",
"6": "<p>The command given to the man in linen to take fire from between the wheels, among the cherubim — the connection between the wheels (<em>ofanim</em>) and the cherubim in ch 10 is closer than in ch 1. The wheels were between the cherubim (not beside them as in ch 1), and the fire that had to be collected from them is the altar-fire that burns between the living creatures in 1:13. The altar-fire as judgment-fire is the theological point: what purifies in the cult becomes the instrument of judgment on the city.</p>",
"7": "<p>One cherub stretching out its hand from between the cherubim and putting fire into the hands of the man in linen — the cherub&apos;s active participation in the coal-transfer is unique to ch 10. In ch 1, the living creatures were entirely under divine direction; here one cherub actively assists the judgment-coal transfer. The angelic cooperation in the divine judgment is the throne-chariot vision&apos;s contribution to Ezekiel&apos;s theology of cosmic judgment.</p>",
"8": "<p>The form of a human hand (<em>tavnit yad ʾadam</em>) beneath the wings of the cherubim — this detail adds to the ch 1 description (where only the feet of the living creatures were described). The human hand beneath the wings of the angelic figures has been interpreted as: (1) a hand to grasp or carry objects (as in v7); (2) a symbol of the humanoid character of the divine chariot&apos;s attendants; (3) an architectural reference to the hand-shaped brackets visible in Phoenician and Canaanite ivory carvings of divine attendants.</p>",
"9": "<p>The four wheels beside each cherub — &quot;the appearance of the wheels was like chrysolite&quot; (<em>keʿein tarshish</em>) — the gem identification follows ch 1:16 precisely. The mineral <em>tarshish</em> (translated variously as topaz, chrysolite, or beryl) was a Mediterranean luxury import whose shimmer suggested the metallic fire-color of the visionary wheels. The ANE throne-chariot was a functional vehicle drawn by divine animals (the divine horses of 2 Kgs 6:17 and Ps 68:17); Ezekiel&apos;s chariot has wheels with their own living spirit (<em>ruach ḥayyah</em>) inside them.</p>",
"10": "<p>The four wheels the same appearance, each as if a wheel within a wheel — the &quot;wheel within a wheel&quot; (<em>ofan betoikh ofan</em>) description has fascinated interpreters and illustrators for centuries. The most likely ANE referent is the double-wheel chariot used in Mesopotamian military vehicles (visible on Assyrian reliefs): an outer wheel with wide spokes and an inner solid disk creating a compound wheel structure. The visionary adaptation makes the wheels able to move in all four directions without turning.</p>",
"11": "<p>The directional movement without turning — the same feature as in 1:12, 17: &quot;they went in any of the four directions without turning as they went.&quot; This technical description of the wheels&apos; omnidirectional capacity without rotation is the most machine-like element of the entire vision. It distinguishes the divine chariot from all human vehicles and has attracted engineering interpretation (Jakob Lenz, 1696 and many later) as well as mystical interpretation (the Merkabah tradition).</p>",
"12": "<p>The bodies, backs, hands, and wings of the cherubim — and the wheels — full of eyes all around: the eyes covering every surface of the chariot-living-creatures is the omniscience motif made visual. Ps 139:7-12 (&quot;whither shall I go from your Spirit?&quot;) is the theological equivalent: YHWH&apos;s awareness is omnidirectional and total. In Mesopotamian iconography, divine figures are sometimes depicted with multiple eyes or with a star-pattern that can suggest omniscient vision; Ezekiel&apos;s eye-covered wheels make the divine omniscience structurally intrinsic to the chariot itself.</p>",
"13": "<p>&quot;As for the wheels, they were called in my hearing: the whirling wheels&quot; (<em>hagalgal</em>) — the naming of the wheels (&quot;the Whirler&quot; or &quot;the Roller&quot;) by an audible divine declaration within the vision is unique in Ezekiel. The term <em>galgal</em> (wheel/rolling thing) is used in Ps 77:18 and 83:14 for the rolling thunder or tumbleweeds of the storm-theophany; here it becomes the proper name for the chariot-wheels.</p>",
"14": "<p>The four faces of the cherubim: first face is a cherub-face, second a human face, third a lion, fourth an eagle — here the ox-face of ch 1 has become a cherub-face. The substitution of &quot;cherub&quot; for &quot;ox&quot; in the first face-position may explain why the ox imagery in the Jerusalem temple (the twelve oxen supporting the bronze sea, 1 Kgs 7:25) was a source of contamination — associating cherubim with cattle in the popular mind led to the golden calf worship at Bethel (1 Kgs 12:28-29). The cherub-face replacing the ox-face corrects this association.</p>",
"15": "<p>The identification of the living creatures from ch 1 as cherubim — made explicit in v20 as well — grounds the visionary beings in the established OT iconography of the ark-cherubim (Exod 25:18-22; 1 Kgs 6:23-28). The cherubim of the Most Holy Place were winged figures flanking the mercy-seat above the ark; the cherubim of Ezekiel&apos;s vision are their cosmic counterparts, the living creatures that bear the divine throne across the heavens and through history.</p>",
"16": "<p>The wheels rising when the cherubim rise — the unity of living creatures and wheels is the distinctive feature of the chariot vision. In ANE military chariots, the horses or oxen and the chariot were distinct; Ezekiel&apos;s vision integrates the motive power (the living creatures) and the vehicle (the wheels) into a single organism. The theological implication: YHWH&apos;s mobility across creation is not mediated through separate components but is intrinsic to a unified divine presence.</p>",
"17": "<p>The spirit of the living creatures in the wheels — the same as 1:21. The <em>ruach ḥayyah</em> (spirit of the living creature) animating the wheels directly, with no mechanical intermediary, is the vision&apos;s answer to the question of what makes the divine chariot move. The answer is not mechanical or cosmological but personal: the living spirit that is in the living creatures is also in the wheels, giving them their omnidirectional mobility.</p>",
"18": "<p>The glory of YHWH departing from the threshold of the house and standing over the cherubim — the second step of the departure sequence. The glory has moved from (1) the cherub-throne in the Most Holy Place to (2) the temple threshold (v4) to (3) above the cherubim in the inner court. The graduated withdrawal from the temple is the theological preparation for the final departure in 11:22-23 to the Mount of Olives and then to Babylon (implied in the deportation-context).</p>",
"19": "<p>The cherubim lifting their wings and rising from the earth before Ezekiel&apos;s eyes — the departure from the Jerusalem temple is a historically unprecedented event in Israelite theology. The temple had been the permanent dwelling of YHWH (&quot;a place for you to dwell forever,&quot; 1 Kgs 8:13); its abandonment by the divine glory was theologically catastrophic. The departure moves to the east gate — the same gate through which the glory will return in 43:1-4, completing the structural arc of the book&apos;s theology.</p>",
"20": "<p>The explicit identification of the living creatures from ch 1 as the cherubim beneath the God of Israel — Ezekiel confirms that the Babylonian vision and the Jerusalem temple vision are of the same divine realities. The cherubim of the heavenly throne-chariot are the cosmic counterparts of the golden cherubim in the Most Holy Place. The vision asserts the continuity of YHWH&apos;s presence across the radical geographical disruption of the exile: the God who was in the Jerusalem temple is the same God now present at the Chebar canal in Babylon.</p>",
"21": "<p>The four faces and four wings of each cherub, with human hands beneath their wings — the cross-reference to ch 1 is the literary device that confirms the identity of the two vision-experiences. Ezekiel&apos;s vision at the Chebar (1:1) and the vision in Jerusalem (8:3) are connected by these repeated details: YHWH&apos;s presence is not geographically restricted despite the exile&apos;s apparent evidence to the contrary.</p>",
"22": "<p>The faces identical in appearance to the living creatures of ch 1 — the precision of the identification (same appearance, same forward movement) confirms that the throne-chariot is a consistent reality, not a shifting vision. The theological claim of chs 1-11 taken together: YHWH&apos;s glory was in Jerusalem, witnessed and cataloged its abominations, departed in stages through the east gate, and now accompanies the exiles in Babylon. The exile is not divine abandonment — it is divine accompaniment. The prophet who saw the glory at the Chebar (ch 1) also sees it depart Jerusalem (chs 10-11), confirming that YHWH himself is in exile with his people.</p>"
}
}

